Goto in Bash
============

I've been playing around with Bash, and it's quickly becoming my all time
favourite language.  There are some pitfalls and something that requires
a bit of caution, but I like it overall.

Bash has no `goto`.

This is terrible.  I must fix this.  Yes, I wrote my own goto function.

This is the code I wrote, it's pretty crappy but it kinda works.

```
#!/usr/bin/env bash
# add the following two lines at the top of your script
set -a; 
[[ ! "$script" ]] && script="$0"
# your functions here
func () {
  echo "i'm in a function"
}
# end of functions
# this must be declared after all other functions
goto () { exec bash <<< "$(sed -n "1,$LINENO p; /^: $1\$/,\$ p" "$script")" ; }
# and now, let's goto!
echo first
variable=hello
goto foo
echo second
# this is a label
: bar
echo third
goto last
: foo
func
echo fourth
goto bar
: last
echo end
echo "$variable"
```

Why it sucks
--

1. You _have_ to export all your variables
2. All the functions must be declared at the beginning of the script
3. There's no way to export arrays

Is there anything better?
--

A quick google search (which I should have done before writing it) reported
this nice(r) way of using `goto` statements in bash:

[http://bobcopeland.com/blog/2012/10/goto-in-bash/](http://bobcopeland.com/blog/2012/10/goto-in-bash/)

I didn't really like `sed | grep` part, but it's way better than my version.
My labels are still better, as they're valid shell code and don't need to be
grepped away.

Inspired by this, one could just write:

`goto () { eval $(sed -n "/^: $1\$/,\$p"); exit $? ; }`

Pretty neat, isn't it?

But... this means i cannot use comments in labels :(  Ok, let's change it to:

`goto () { eval "$(sed -n "/^: $1[[:space:]]*\(#.*\)*\$/,\$p" "$0")"; exit $?; }`

That's better, but it just ignores `goto`s that point to inexistant labels.

This is the version with error checking:  (remember: real programmers need no
error checking, but it's up to you)

```
goto () {
  cmd=$(sed -n "/^: $1[[:space:]]*\(#.*\)*\$/,\$p" "$0")
  if [[ $cmd ]] ; then
    eval "$cmd"
    exit $?
  else
    echo "Label not found: $1" >&2
    exit 1
  fi
}
```

Writing unreadable bash code has never been easier.

